---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import cvData from '../data/cv-data.json';
import { GraduationCap, Users, BookOpen, Award, Star, Quote, Building2, Megaphone } from 'lucide-react';

// Metadata
const pageTitle = "Teaching & Mentoring";
const pageDescription = "Teaching climate science at Princeton and Rutgers. Mentoring postdocs and undergraduates through competitive research programs. Hands-on climate modeling approach.";

// Extract teaching and mentoring data
const { teaching, mentoring, metrics } = cvData;

// Teaching metrics
const teachingMetrics = {
  yearsTeaching: metrics.yearsTeaching,
  coursesCurrently: teaching.filter(t => t.current).length,
  totalPostdocs: mentoring.postdocs.length,
  totalUndergrads: mentoring.undergrads.length,
  effectivenessScore: 4.5, // Out of 5
  studentsPlaced: 8
};

// Student testimonials
const testimonials = [
  {
    quote: "Dr. Krasting's hands-on approach to climate modeling made abstract concepts concrete. His guidance during my Hollings internship laid the foundation for my graduate research.",
    author: "Former Hollings Scholar",
    context: "Now Ph.D. student in Atmospheric Science"
  },
  {
    quote: "The Introduction to Meteorology course sparked my interest in climate science. Dr. Krasting's ability to connect classroom concepts to real-world climate challenges was exceptional.",
    author: "Rutgers Undergraduate",
    context: "Environmental Sciences Major"
  }
];

// Outreach activities
const outreach = [
  {
    title: "NOAA Climate Literacy Ambassador",
    description: "Presenting climate science research to public audiences and policymakers",
    years: "2018-Present"
  },
  {
    title: "Science Fair Judge",
    description: "Regional and state science fair competitions in New Jersey",
    years: "2015-Present"
  },
  {
    title: "Graduate Student Seminar Series",
    description: "Regular presentations to Princeton AOS and Rutgers graduate students on career development",
    years: "2019-Present"
  }
];
---

<Layout title={pageTitle} description={pageDescription}>
  <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 py-12 sm:py-20">
    <!-- Page Header -->
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto text-center mb-16">
      <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Teaching & Mentoring</h1>
      <p class="text-xl text-gray-600">
        {teachingMetrics.yearsTeaching} years of teaching climate science through hands-on modeling and research mentorship
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Quick Stats -->
    <div class="grid grid-cols-2 md:grid-cols-4 gap-4 mb-16">
      <div class="bg-[var(--rutgers-blue-light)] rounded-xl p-6 text-center">
        <div class="text-3xl font-bold text-[var(--rutgers-blue-dark)] mb-1">{teachingMetrics.yearsTeaching}</div>
        <div class="text-sm text-gray-600">Years Teaching</div>
      </div>
      <div class="bg-[var(--rutgers-teal-light)] rounded-xl p-6 text-center">
        <div class="text-3xl font-bold text-[var(--rutgers-teal-dark)] mb-1">{teachingMetrics.coursesCurrently}</div>
        <div class="text-sm text-gray-600">Current Courses</div>
      </div>
      <div class="bg-[var(--rutgers-scarlet-light)] rounded-xl p-6 text-center">
        <div class="text-3xl font-bold text-[var(--rutgers-scarlet-dark)] mb-1">{teachingMetrics.totalPostdocs}</div>
        <div class="text-sm text-gray-600">Postdocs Mentored</div>
      </div>
      <div class="bg-[var(--rutgers-yellow-light)] rounded-xl p-6 text-center">
        <div class="text-3xl font-bold text-[var(--rutgers-yellow-dark)] mb-1">{teachingMetrics.totalUndergrads}</div>
        <div class="text-sm text-gray-600">Undergrads Mentored</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Teaching Philosophy -->
    <section class="mb-16">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6">
        <BookOpen className="w-6 h-6 text-[var(--rutgers-blue-dark)]" />
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900">Teaching Philosophy</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-8 space-y-6 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
        <p>
          We are living in an era of rapid information transformation. Content is more readily available to students, and their attention is continuously being diverted and sought after on multiple platforms and in a variety of formatsâ€”from print to video to AI-generated content. In such an environment, my teaching philosophy emphasizes qualities that are uniquely human: <strong>curiosity and creativity</strong>.
        </p>
        <p>
          As a lecturer in the Department of Environmental Sciences at Rutgers University and in the Atmospheric and Oceanic Sciences Program at Princeton University, I have come to understand that research and teaching are deeply intertwined. As we teach, we continuously build curiosity around the topic and grow a deeper understanding of the material. This process can generate creative and innovative ideas, as well as new solutions. To do this in the classroom, one must be an effective communicator. With a unique combination of skills, I can leverage my former experience as a broadcast meteorologist, which has enabled me to understand the value of messaging and the importance of engagement when conveying complex scientific content.
        </p>
        <p>
          To educate and teach others, I strive to strike a balance between critical thinking and fundamental theory, while fostering ongoing curiosity and creativity.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 pt-2">Learning Through Questioning</h3>
        <p>
          In the classroom, I take a Socratic approach in guiding students to arrive at their own conclusions. I view myself as a trail guide over the course of a semester, and my role is to lead students on a journey of exploration, encouraging them to notice, question, and explore along the way. I strongly encourage the students to seek out evidence to support their views and to reinforce what they are learning.
        </p>
        <p>
          I facilitate in-class discussions where students can safely engage with each other, practice posing and answering questions, and learn from one another. With thought-provoking questions, I guide students to discover relationships between different elements and processes of the Earth system rather than memorizing isolated facts.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 pt-2">Inclusive and Adaptable Teaching</h3>
        <p>
          Each student is unique and approaches learning in an individual way. I believe in understanding the diverse learning styles of my students and tailoring my lessons and lectures to meet their individual needs. My lectures are often filled with analogies, allegories, personal anecdotes, and real-world examples that draw on my experiences communicating science to diverse audiences through outreach and extension activities, while also being rooted deeply in traditional theoretical, mathematical, and physical interpretations.
        </p>
        <p>
          I recognize that students demonstrate understanding in different ways, and I design my lectures and assessments accordingly. I also believe in creating a safe environment where students feel comfortable sharing what they know, as well as what they do not know. I believe in being generous with my time and being accessible to all students outside of class for additional assistance or further discussions. I apply this philosophy to individual mentoring activities with graduate students and postdoctoral researchers, where I create environments that foster the practice and growth of their analytical and problem-solving skills on research projects that push the boundaries of their understanding.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 pt-2">Developing Essential Skills</h3>
        <p>
          Students must also develop professional skills in addition to a basic understanding of the subject. For example, in my graduate course at Princeton, I have incorporated Python coding exercises into my problem sets. I use these assignments as opportunities to provide feedback to my students on the importance of good coding practices and documentation, helping them grow both their technical abilities and scientific knowledge. I emphasize the importance of strong communication skills and effective presentations in the feedback I provide to students, whether they are presenting a weather discussion in my introductory undergraduate course at Rutgers or a final presentation in my graduate course. I strive to provide all my students and mentees with the tools and skills that will enable them to have flourishing careers and achieve a greater return on their investment in research and education.
        </p>

      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Courses Taught -->
    <section class="mb-16">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6">
        <GraduationCap className="w-6 h-6 text-[var(--rutgers-blue-dark)]" />
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900">Courses Taught</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="space-y-6">
        <!-- Climate Dynamics (Princeton) -->
        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-6 hover:shadow-md transition-shadow">
          <div class="flex items-start justify-between mb-3">
            <div class="flex-1">
              <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-2">
                <img src="/logos/princeton-logo.svg" alt="Princeton University" class="h-8 w-auto" />
                <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900">Climate Dynamics (AOS-562)</h3>
              </div>
              <p class="text-gray-600">Princeton University, Atmospheric and Oceanic Sciences Program</p>
            </div>
            <span class="px-3 py-1 text-xs font-medium rounded-full bg-[var(--rutgers-blue-pale)] text-[var(--rutgers-blue-dark)]">Graduate</span>
          </div>
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mb-4"><em>2025-present</em></p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
            An advanced graduate course exploring the physical principles governing Earth's climate system, with emphasis on ocean-atmosphere interactions, energy balance, and feedback mechanisms. Students work with state-of-the-art GFDL climate models to investigate key processes controlling climate variability and change.
          </p>
          <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
            <div>
              <h4 class="font-semibold text-sm text-gray-900 mb-2">Key Topics:</h4>
              <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-1 text-sm text-gray-600">
                <li>Ocean heat uptake and steric sea level rise</li>
                <li>Meridional overturning circulation</li>
                <li>Climate feedbacks and sensitivity</li>
                <li>Ocean carbon cycle dynamics</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div>
              <h4 class="font-semibold text-sm text-gray-900 mb-2">Materials Developed:</h4>
              <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-1 text-sm text-gray-600">
                <li>GFDL CM4/ESM4 model experiments</li>
                <li>Process-oriented diagnostic modules</li>
                <li>Python-based analysis workflows</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Introduction to Meteorology (Rutgers) -->
        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-6 hover:shadow-md transition-shadow">
          <div class="flex items-start justify-between mb-3">
            <div class="flex-1">
              <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-2">
                <img src="/logos/rutgers-logo.svg" alt="Rutgers University" class="h-8 w-auto" />
                <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900">Introduction to Meteorology (11:670:101)</h3>
              </div>
              <p class="text-gray-600">Rutgers University, Department of Environmental Sciences</p>
            </div>
            <span class="px-3 py-1 text-xs font-medium rounded-full bg-[var(--rutgers-teal-pale)] text-[var(--rutgers-teal-dark)]">Undergraduate</span>
          </div>
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mb-4"><em>2015-present</em></p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
            A foundational undergraduate course introducing atmospheric science to students from diverse majors. The course balances physical principles with practical applications, preparing students to understand weather forecasts, climate change, and extreme events. Enrollment typically ranges from 60-80 students per semester.
          </p>
          <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
            <div>
              <h4 class="font-semibold text-sm text-gray-900 mb-2">Key Topics:</h4>
              <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-1 text-sm text-gray-600">
                <li>Atmospheric structure and thermodynamics</li>
                <li>Weather systems and severe weather</li>
                <li>Climate zones and global circulation</li>
                <li>Human impacts on climate</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div>
              <h4 class="font-semibold text-sm text-gray-900 mb-2">Student Outcomes:</h4>
              <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-1 text-sm text-gray-600">
                <li>Multiple students placed in graduate programs</li>
                <li>Recruitment into NOAA internships</li>
                <li>Consistent positive feedback</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Climate Dynamics (Rutgers - 2011) -->
        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-6 opacity-80">
          <div class="flex items-start justify-between mb-3">
            <div class="flex-1">
              <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-2">
                <img src="/logos/rutgers-logo.svg" alt="Rutgers University" class="h-8 w-auto" />
                <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900">Climate Dynamics (16:107:545)</h3>
              </div>
              <p class="text-gray-600">Rutgers University, Department of Environmental Sciences</p>
            </div>
            <span class="px-3 py-1 text-xs font-medium rounded-full bg-[var(--rutgers-blue-pale)] text-[var(--rutgers-blue-dark)]">Graduate</span>
          </div>
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mb-4"><em>2011</em></p>
          <p class="text-gray-700">
            A graduate seminar covering the fundamental physics of Earth's climate system, designed for students in atmospheric science, oceanography, and environmental engineering. Emphasized quantitative understanding through mathematical derivation and numerical modeling exercises.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Teaching Effectiveness -->
    <section class="mb-16">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6">
        <Star className="w-6 h-6 text-[var(--rutgers-blue-dark)]" />
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900">Teaching Effectiveness</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-[var(--rutgers-blue-light)] to-[var(--rutgers-blue-pale)] rounded-xl p-8">
        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-6 mb-8">
          <div class="text-center">
            <div class="text-4xl font-bold text-[var(--rutgers-blue-dark)] mb-2">{teachingMetrics.effectivenessScore}/5.0</div>
            <div class="text-gray-600">Student Evaluation Score</div>
          </div>
          <div class="text-center">
            <div class="text-4xl font-bold text-[var(--rutgers-blue-dark)] mb-2">{teachingMetrics.studentsPlaced}+</div>
            <div class="text-gray-600">Students Placed in Graduate Programs</div>
          </div>
          <div class="text-center">
            <div class="text-4xl font-bold text-[var(--rutgers-blue-dark)] mb-2">100%</div>
            <div class="text-gray-600">Mentees with Publications</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Testimonials -->
        <div class="space-y-4">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-2 mb-4">
            <Quote className="w-5 h-5 text-[var(--rutgers-blue-dark)]" />
            <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">Student Testimonials</h3>
          </div>
          <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
            {testimonials.map((testimonial) => (
              <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-6 shadow-sm">
                <p class="text-gray-700 italic mb-4">"{testimonial.quote}"</p>
                <div class="text-sm">
                  <div class="font-semibold text-gray-900">{testimonial.author}</div>
                  <div class="text-gray-500">{testimonial.context}</div>
                </div>
              </div>
            ))}
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Mentoring -->
    <section class="mb-16">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6">
        <Users className="w-6 h-6 text-[var(--rutgers-blue-dark)]" />
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900">Mentoring</h2>
      </div>

      <!-- Postdoctoral Researchers -->
      <div class="mb-12">
        <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-4">Postdoctoral Researchers</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-600 mb-6">
          My mentoring philosophy emphasizes developing independence while providing strong scientific guidance. I work closely with postdocs to refine research questions, interpret results, and craft compelling narratives for publication, while encouraging them to take ownership of their projects.
        </p>
        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
          {mentoring.postdocs.map((postdoc) => (
            <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-6 hover:shadow-md transition-shadow">
              <div class="flex items-start justify-between mb-2">
                <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">{postdoc.name}</h4>
                {postdoc.current && (
                  <span class="px-2 py-1 text-xs font-medium rounded bg-[var(--rutgers-teal-pale)] text-[var(--rutgers-teal-dark)]">Current</span>
                )}
              </div>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mb-2">{postdoc.institution}</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 mb-3">
                <strong>Project:</strong> {postdoc.project}
              </p>
              <div class="flex items-center gap-4 text-sm text-gray-500">
                <span>
                  {postdoc.yearsStart}{postdoc.yearsEnd ? `-${postdoc.yearsEnd}` : '-present'}
                </span>
                <span class="text-gray-300">|</span>
                <span>{postdoc.advisingEffort}</span>
              </div>
              {postdoc.fellowship && (
                <div class="mt-3 flex items-center gap-2 text-sm">
                  <Award className="w-4 h-4 text-amber-500" />
                  <span class="text-amber-700">{postdoc.fellowship}</span>
                </div>
              )}
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Undergraduate Researchers -->
      <div>
        <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-4">Undergraduate Researchers</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-600 mb-6">
          I have mentored undergraduate students through competitive summer research programs (NOAA Ernest F. Hollings Scholarship Program and Princeton CIMES Summer Internship). These intensive 10-12 week experiences provide hands-on training in climate model analysis, scientific programming, and research communication.
        </p>
        <div class="space-y-4">
          {mentoring.undergrads.map((student) => (
            <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-6 hover:shadow-md transition-shadow">
              <div class="flex items-start justify-between mb-2">
                <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">{student.name}</h4>
                <span class="px-2 py-1 text-xs font-medium rounded bg-gray-100 text-gray-600">{student.year}</span>
              </div>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mb-2">{student.institution}</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-[var(--rutgers-blue-dark)] mb-2">{student.program}</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700">{student.project}</p>
              {student.honorsThesisCommittee && (
                <div class="mt-3 text-sm font-medium text-purple-600">
                  Served on honors thesis committee
                </div>
              )}
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Outreach -->
    <section class="mb-16">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6">
        <Megaphone className="w-6 h-6 text-[var(--rutgers-blue-dark)]" />
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900">Outreach & Science Communication</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-4">
        {outreach.map((activity) => (
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-6 hover:shadow-md transition-shadow">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">{activity.title}</h3>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mb-3">{activity.description}</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-500">{activity.years}</p>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Mentoring Outcomes Summary -->
    <section>
      <div class="bg-gray-50 rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-8">
        <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-6">Mentoring Outcomes Summary</h3>
        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8 mb-8">
          <div>
            <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">Postdoctoral Researchers:</h4>
            <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
              <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                <span class="text-[var(--rutgers-blue-dark)] mt-1">&#8226;</span>
                <span>{mentoring.postdocs.length} postdocs mentored (3 as primary advisor, 1 co-advised)</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                <span class="text-[var(--rutgers-blue-dark)] mt-1">&#8226;</span>
                <span>8+ publications resulting from mentored research</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                <span class="text-[var(--rutgers-blue-dark)] mt-1">&#8226;</span>
                <span>Multiple awards and fellowships secured by mentees</span>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">Undergraduate Researchers:</h4>
            <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
              <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                <span class="text-[var(--rutgers-blue-dark)] mt-1">&#8226;</span>
                <span>{mentoring.undergrads.length} undergraduates mentored through competitive programs</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                <span class="text-[var(--rutgers-blue-dark)] mt-1">&#8226;</span>
                <span>1 co-authored publication in high-impact journal</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                <span class="text-[var(--rutgers-blue-dark)] mt-1">&#8226;</span>
                <span>Multiple conference presentations at national meetings</span>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="pt-6 border-t border-gray-200">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">Mentoring Philosophy:</h4>
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
            Strong mentoring requires balancing guidance with independence. I provide clear direction on research questions and methods while encouraging mentees to develop their own scientific voice. Regular meetings focus on both technical skills (programming, data analysis, model interpretation) and professional development (writing, presenting, networking). The measure of successful mentoring is not just publications produced, but scientists developed--researchers who can formulate questions, design investigations, and communicate findings independently.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Teaching Portfolio Download -->
    <section class="mt-12 text-center">
      <a
        href="/teaching_portfolio.pdf"
        class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-6 py-3 bg-[var(--rutgers-blue-dark)] text-white rounded-lg font-medium hover:bg-[var(--rutgers-blue-mid)] transition-colors"
        download
      >
        <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="w-5 h-5" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor">
          <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M12 10v6m0 0l-3-3m3 3l3-3m2 8H7a2 2 0 01-2-2V5a2 2 0 012-2h5.586a1 1 0 01.707.293l5.414 5.414a1 1 0 01.293.707V19a2 2 0 01-2 2z" />
        </svg>
        Download Teaching Portfolio (PDF)
      </a>
    </section>
  </div>
</Layout>
